            <div id="dataTypesResults" class="buttonPar" style="display: none;">
                What is Data Types and how do we incorporate into coding?
                Data Types are important since it allow programmers to store different types of data. You can have <em><b><mark>string, boolean,numbers, undefined, null, object, and array data types.</em></b></mark>
                Let’s tackle on how to write each data types using a variable to store a data.....<br>
                <br>The <em><b><mark>string</em></b></mark> data type can use either single or double quotes.
                <br>
                <pre>let grocery = “avocado”;<br>let grocery = 'avocado';</pre>
                <br>
                The <em><b><mark>boolean</em></b></mark> data type can have two values of either true or false.<br>
                <pre>let fruit = orange;<br>let vegetable = iceCream;<br>fruit = true;<br>vegetable = false;</pre>
                <br>
                The <em><b><mark>numbers</em></b></mark> data type can be written as with or without decimals.<br>
                <pre>let x = 5;<br>let y = 5.00;</pre><br>
                The <em><b><mark>undefined</em></b></mark> data type is when a variable has been declared, but has not been assigned a value.<br>
                <pre>let x;<br>let y = "fruits";<br>console.log(x);
                <br>The output will be <em>undefined</em> since there is no value assigned to x.
                <br>console.log(y);
                <br>The output will be <em>fruits</em> since there is a value assigned to y as fruits.</pre>
                <br>The <em><b><mark>null</em></b></mark> is when value does not exist. In Javascript, <em><b><mark>null</em></b></mark> is an object.<br>
                <pre>let x = null;<br>console.log(x);<br>The output will be <em><b><mark>null</em></b></mark> since it is assigned as null.</pre><br>
                <em><b><mark>Array</em></b></mark> used for storing multiple values in single variable using square brackets and separated by using commas.<br>
                <pre>let fruits = ['grapes', 'oranges', 'apples'];</pre><br>
                <em><b><mark>Objects</em></b></mark> allows to store collections of data by using curly brackets. An object contains properties which are defined as key value pairs.<br>
                <pre>let fruits = {<br>    name = "apples";<br>    cost = 1;<br>};</pre><br>
                    In this example, an object represents fruits. <b>name</b> and <b>cost</b> represent <b><em><mark>keys</b></em></mark>. The
                    <em><b>apples</em></b> and <em><b>1</em></b> represent <em></em><b>values</b><em>. </li>
            
